WEBVTT

00:02.120 --> 00:03.750
[ Crystal Fighters'
"Wild Ones" plays ]

00:03.750 --> 00:05.580
[ Horns honking ]

00:05.580 --> 00:08.830
♪♪

00:08.830 --> 00:12.500
Meredith: Almost all human cells
reproduce on a cycle.

00:12.500 --> 00:14.000
♪ I thought I was a star ♪

00:14.000 --> 00:17.290
Up to 10% of your heart
is replaced each year.

00:17.290 --> 00:20.960
♪ From the sky I freefall ♪

00:20.960 --> 00:23.330
Red blood cells are replaced
every four months.

00:23.330 --> 00:25.170
Thank you.

00:25.170 --> 00:27.040
Skin cells, every two weeks.

00:27.040 --> 00:30.710
♪ 'Cause I thought
I was a star ♪

00:30.710 --> 00:32.290
Uh.

00:32.290 --> 00:34.040
♪ How long, tell me how long
can this go on? ♪

00:34.040 --> 00:35.210
Want to get a pizza
or something?

00:35.210 --> 00:36.500
I know a great place.

00:36.500 --> 00:39.330
Well, it's late.
I should, uh, go to sleep.

00:39.330 --> 00:41.250
It's only 8:30
in Seattle.

00:41.250 --> 00:42.670
Yeah, but we're not in Seattle.

00:42.670 --> 00:45.000
We're in New York,
and we are doing

00:45.000 --> 00:49.290
a complicated surgery on
New York time in the morning.

00:49.290 --> 00:51.750
Okay, fine.
Room service...

00:51.750 --> 00:55.040
in bed, then sleep.

00:55.040 --> 00:57.710
We agreed.
Just sex, no sleepovers.

00:57.710 --> 00:59.040
But we're out of town.

00:59.040 --> 01:00.710
- Bend the rules.
- No, it's not a rule,

01:00.710 --> 01:03.620
so much as the basic tenet
of this relationship.

01:03.620 --> 01:05.670
Which is that it's not
a relationship? Right.

01:05.670 --> 01:07.830
No complications.
My life is already full of them.

01:07.830 --> 01:10.670
But it's not that complicated.
W-We have adjoining rooms.

01:10.670 --> 01:12.040
They're practically the same.

01:12.040 --> 01:13.210
And yet, they are not.

01:13.210 --> 01:14.710
But neurons,

01:14.710 --> 01:17.250
the cells that make up
the brain and spinal cord,

01:17.250 --> 01:18.960
don't regenerate.

01:18.960 --> 01:21.670
I feel used!

01:21.670 --> 01:23.540
Objectified!

01:23.540 --> 01:25.210
Hungry!

01:25.210 --> 01:26.830
♪ And we rage on
till we're blazing in the sun ♪

01:26.830 --> 01:28.540
Okay.
What will it take for you

01:28.540 --> 01:29.960
to let me go to sleep tonight,
guilt-free?

01:29.960 --> 01:31.420
♪ La la la la la la ♪
♪ How long? ♪

01:31.420 --> 01:32.960
Pizza for breakfast.

01:32.960 --> 01:33.960
Deal.

01:33.960 --> 01:35.880
♪ And we rage on ♪

01:35.880 --> 01:38.170
[ Door closes ] ♪ Till
we're blazing in the sun ♪

01:38.170 --> 01:43.170
♪♪

01:43.170 --> 01:45.750
I'm still questioning pizza
as a breakfast food,

01:45.750 --> 01:47.420
but this is a really excellent slice.
Mm-hmm.

01:47.420 --> 01:48.500
How'd you know about this place?

01:48.500 --> 01:49.710
Mm.

01:49.710 --> 01:51.620
It was part of my wish.

01:51.620 --> 01:54.000
You wished for perfect pizza?

01:54.000 --> 01:55.460
From a fairy godmother?

01:55.460 --> 01:57.250
Cancer kids who are in
as bad a shape as I was

01:57.250 --> 01:58.330
get wishes.

01:59.540 --> 02:01.170
Osteosarcoma.
Age 10.

02:01.170 --> 02:03.040
Full remission.

02:03.040 --> 02:05.790
What'd you wish for?

02:05.790 --> 02:08.000
Baseball game at Shea Stadium.
[ Chuckling ] Yeah.

02:08.000 --> 02:10.789
I got to meet my favorite
player, Dwight Gooden.

02:10.789 --> 02:14.670
I remember thinking,
"I'll be back."

02:14.670 --> 02:16.960
And the next time was with
the Mariners as the team doctor.

02:16.960 --> 02:18.250
That is impressive.

02:18.250 --> 02:19.670
Nothing will beat that
first time out here.

02:19.670 --> 02:22.000
I ate here five times.

02:22.000 --> 02:24.330
Even got a picture out front.
[ Chuckles ]

02:24.330 --> 02:26.080
Oh, and there was this
great donut place

02:26.080 --> 02:27.750
right around the corner.
Um...

02:27.750 --> 02:29.330
Gotham Donuts!

02:29.330 --> 02:32.750
Oh! Best glazed donut
I've ever had.

02:32.750 --> 02:34.120
That was, uh...

02:34.120 --> 02:36.420
Well, that was our last trip
together before the divorce.

02:36.420 --> 02:39.710
Uh, I guess this city
reminds me of better times.

02:41.170 --> 02:44.880
That is the exact
opposite of me.

02:44.880 --> 02:46.210
I grew up here.

02:46.210 --> 02:47.960
Well, not exactly here.

02:47.960 --> 02:51.040
I was like half an hour away
in Westchester.

02:51.040 --> 02:55.580
But my life in New York was
definitely not better times.

02:57.790 --> 03:01.000
Wait. You're saying
we could've had donuts?!

03:02.380 --> 03:06.040
[ Siren wailing, horn honks ]

03:06.040 --> 03:09.120
Admit it.
14 blocks was not that far.

03:09.120 --> 03:10.790
And when you walk,
you see things

03:10.790 --> 03:12.420
you never would have from a cab.
You're right.

03:12.420 --> 03:14.620
We totally would've missed
that group of mimes

03:14.620 --> 03:17.000
yelling at each other. And
the rat dragging the bagel.

03:17.000 --> 03:18.250
[ Laughing ]
That was so gross.

03:18.250 --> 03:19.460
- Amy?
- [ Gasps ]

03:19.460 --> 03:20.710
Oh, my God!

03:20.710 --> 03:21.670
Uh...
Amy!

03:21.670 --> 03:23.120
Nancy!

03:23.120 --> 03:24.790
[ Gasps ] Yeah.

03:24.790 --> 03:26.330
Nancy Shepherd.
[ Chuckles ]

03:26.330 --> 03:28.710
Oh, Amelia's sister.

03:28.710 --> 03:30.080
You must be Owen.

03:30.080 --> 03:31.330
Yes!

03:31.330 --> 03:33.920
This is my husband.

03:33.920 --> 03:37.170
♪♪

03:37.170 --> 03:38.580
Nice to meet you, Nancy.

03:38.580 --> 03:39.960
I've heard so much about you.

03:39.960 --> 03:41.790
Do you work here?

03:41.790 --> 03:44.830
I'm covering the chief of OB's
maternity leave.

03:44.830 --> 03:46.040
Ironic, right?

03:46.040 --> 03:47.040
How about you?

03:47.040 --> 03:48.290
Everything okay?

03:48.290 --> 03:49.750
Yeah.

03:49.750 --> 03:51.880
No... We're here
for a patient.

03:51.880 --> 03:53.290
All the way from Seattle?
Wow.

03:53.290 --> 03:55.460
You must be very in demand.

03:55.460 --> 03:57.460
I guess that's why
we never hear from you.

03:57.460 --> 03:59.380
Yep.

03:59.380 --> 04:02.580
Been pretty busy
since I saw you last.

04:02.580 --> 04:05.420
I operated on
Catherine Fox herself.

04:05.420 --> 04:06.420
Might've read about it.

04:06.420 --> 04:08.420
Also got married.

04:08.420 --> 04:09.670
Aah.

04:09.670 --> 04:12.330
Right. Welcome to the family.
[ Chuckles ]

04:12.330 --> 04:15.420
We've got some pretty
deep-seated dysfunction,

04:15.420 --> 04:17.959
but [chuckles] you've probably
figured that out by now.

04:17.959 --> 04:19.670
Ah, what family doesn't?

04:19.670 --> 04:20.790
Do you have sisters?

04:21.959 --> 04:24.500
I do, so I get it.

04:24.500 --> 04:26.620
We should catch up.

04:26.620 --> 04:27.920
Come for dinner, both of you.

04:27.920 --> 04:30.040
Ah! We can't.
[ Chuckles ]

04:30.040 --> 04:31.620
Taking off tonight.

04:31.620 --> 04:33.880
She's got a big surgery
in Seattle tomorrow.

04:33.880 --> 04:35.290
I do.
Oh.

04:35.290 --> 04:37.920
Well, at least I got to see you.

04:37.920 --> 04:40.420
Halley's Comet comes around
more than you do.

04:40.420 --> 04:42.670
[ Elevator bell dings ]
[ Chuckles ]

04:42.670 --> 04:44.580
Oh, uh...

04:44.580 --> 04:46.830
call Mom sometime, kiddo.

04:46.830 --> 04:48.670
It's the kind thing to do.

04:48.670 --> 04:51.380
♪♪

04:51.380 --> 04:53.500
Okay.

04:53.500 --> 04:54.580
Thanks for that.

04:54.580 --> 04:55.620
[ Clears throat ]

04:55.620 --> 04:57.670
Let's go.
[ Sighs ]

04:57.670 --> 04:59.420
I need to find a shower

04:59.420 --> 05:02.500
so I can wash that "kiddo"
off of me before surgery.

05:10.920 --> 05:12.120
[ Video game beeping ]

05:12.120 --> 05:13.250
Man: You got this!

05:13.250 --> 05:14.330
Oh, man.
[ Chuckles ]

05:14.330 --> 05:15.830
Victory Lane!
You beat me again.

05:15.830 --> 05:17.460
No, man, you totally threw that.
Nice race.

05:17.460 --> 05:19.290
Okay, I'm on way too many pain
meds for you to be losing to me.

05:19.290 --> 05:21.420
Come on.
Hey, Dr. Lew.

05:21.420 --> 05:24.880
Jonah, these are your surgeons,
Doctors Shepherd and Lincoln. Hi.

05:24.880 --> 05:26.330
- Hey.
- Hi.

05:26.330 --> 05:28.540
Uh, this is my brother Brady.
Hi.

05:28.540 --> 05:30.210
You know, I-I would've left him
at home, but he's my ride.

05:30.210 --> 05:31.290
Mm.
[ Laughs ]

05:31.290 --> 05:33.290
Jonah Mays, 18.

05:33.290 --> 05:35.120
He was diagnosed with
progressive kyphoscoliosis

05:35.120 --> 05:36.420
at age 6.

05:36.420 --> 05:38.620
He's had multiple
posterior spine fusions

05:38.620 --> 05:40.710
with instrumentation
from T4 to L5

05:40.710 --> 05:42.170
to correct the curvature.

05:42.170 --> 05:44.380
Yeah, it's, uh, pretty much
my entire spinal cord.

05:44.380 --> 05:47.210
I've had... 15 surgeries
in 12 years.

05:47.210 --> 05:49.710
Some due to growth, some due to
the condition's progression.

05:49.710 --> 05:52.210
Yeah, the metal rods bust
right through his skin.

05:52.210 --> 05:54.670
- Can we take a look?
- Yeah.

05:54.670 --> 05:56.170
You're in good hands, Jonah.

05:56.170 --> 05:57.330
I'll leave you to it.

05:58.960 --> 06:01.330
[ Sighs ]

06:01.330 --> 06:02.920
Looks like the degree
of angulation

06:02.920 --> 06:05.960
has pushed the hardware
off the bolts. Mm.

06:05.960 --> 06:07.250
But you... you can fix
that, though, right?

06:07.250 --> 06:10.000
Dr. Lincoln and I will
remove the rods.

06:10.000 --> 06:13.000
We'll insert a nylon tether,
which will stabilize your spine.

06:13.000 --> 06:14.380
It'll allow room for growth,
which means

06:14.380 --> 06:15.750
fewer surgeries in the future.

06:15.750 --> 06:17.210
Good.

06:17.210 --> 06:19.580
'Cause, uh, you know,
I've got big plans.

06:19.580 --> 06:21.580
I'm moving to California.

06:21.580 --> 06:23.620
I just got accepted
to UC Berkeley.

06:23.620 --> 06:25.670
Go, Bears!
Congratulations.

06:25.670 --> 06:27.460
Thank you. One, uh... One
step at a time, bro.

06:27.460 --> 06:29.960
You're worried.
I get it.

06:29.960 --> 06:32.080
I mean, w-who would take you
to physical therapy

06:32.080 --> 06:33.710
and make sure that you got
to the doctor's on time?

06:33.710 --> 06:34.920
Oh, yeah, that's right.

06:34.920 --> 06:35.960
That's what you've always
done for me.

06:35.960 --> 06:37.420
[ Laughs ]

06:37.420 --> 06:38.750
But I won't need it as much,
all right?

06:38.750 --> 06:39.920
Link: Okay.

06:39.920 --> 06:41.080
We've got your measurements.

06:41.080 --> 06:42.460
We will be back to
prep you for surgery

06:42.460 --> 06:44.500
after we compare them to the scans.
Okay.

06:46.040 --> 06:48.670
Looks like we can use a vats
to anchor the bolts at T3.

06:48.670 --> 06:49.880
Just like we planned.

06:49.880 --> 06:51.290
Should be done by 5:00.

06:51.290 --> 06:53.250
Ah, that gives us almost
another 24 hours

06:53.250 --> 06:55.000
of observation before
we head back to Seattle.

06:55.000 --> 06:56.830
That's amazing news!

06:56.830 --> 06:58.830
I was just gonna leave you
a note, trying to...

06:58.830 --> 07:01.040
What? What?
Uh, what's amazing? What?

07:01.040 --> 07:03.580
I just heard you say
it's at least 24 hours

07:03.580 --> 07:05.670
till your flight leaves,
so you can come for dinner.

07:05.670 --> 07:07.420
John and the kids are upstate
visiting his mom,

07:07.420 --> 07:08.620
so it'll be quiet.

07:08.620 --> 07:10.250
I'll make your favorite
chocolate cream pie.

07:10.250 --> 07:13.960
I... I no longer eat,
um, sugar or gluten.

07:13.960 --> 07:16.210
I'm not taking no for an answer.

07:16.210 --> 07:17.330
Fine, make the pie.

07:17.330 --> 07:18.540
Good.

07:18.540 --> 07:20.380
Text me when you're on your way.

07:20.380 --> 07:21.830
See ya!

07:21.830 --> 07:23.120
Can't wait!

07:25.330 --> 07:27.830
So...

07:27.830 --> 07:29.620
you like pie, right?

07:29.620 --> 07:32.120
♪♪

07:38.120 --> 07:40.380
Five minutes in
the lobby is one thing.

07:40.380 --> 07:41.580
Dinner is a terrible idea,
and I'm not going.

07:41.580 --> 07:42.790
You can't make me go alone...
It's like sending

07:42.790 --> 07:43.880
Red Riding Hood
to visit the wolf.

07:43.880 --> 07:45.670
I'll be having pizza and donuts
in the city.

07:45.670 --> 07:47.120
You're more than welcome
to j... I'm begging.

07:47.120 --> 07:48.580
This is me begging.

07:48.580 --> 07:50.290
Aren't I cute when I beg?

07:50.290 --> 07:51.710
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

07:51.710 --> 07:55.500
Woman on P.A.:
Dr. Kripen, call extension 193.

07:55.500 --> 07:56.500
Link: Okay, Jonah.

07:56.500 --> 07:57.880
Pre-op time.

07:57.880 --> 07:59.540
Are we leaving now?

07:59.540 --> 08:00.920
Why? You winning?

08:00.920 --> 08:03.420
Yeah. But, uh, also...
[clears throat]

08:03.420 --> 08:05.040
Brady went to the cafeteria.

08:05.040 --> 08:06.420
He said he was gonna
go get an apple,

08:06.420 --> 08:08.790
but, uh, I guarantee you
he comes back with fries.

08:08.790 --> 08:11.880
You know, we have this thing
about saying bye to each other

08:11.880 --> 08:15.080
ever since our parents died
six years ago in a car accident.

08:15.080 --> 08:16.670
And, yeah,
it was as dramatic and tragic

08:16.670 --> 08:18.120
as your face is right now.

08:18.120 --> 08:20.290
Oh, sorry. I...
[ Chuckles ]

08:20.290 --> 08:22.290
I'm gonna give you something
to relax you,

08:22.290 --> 08:24.750
and Dr. Lincoln is going to
mark you for surgery.

08:24.750 --> 08:26.750
Cool. What are you
gonna study at Cal?

08:26.750 --> 08:28.170
Uh, environmental science.

08:28.170 --> 08:29.670
Or literature.

08:29.670 --> 08:31.750
Or something
I haven't heard of before.

08:31.750 --> 08:33.000
I-I'm not sure.

08:33.000 --> 08:34.710
Renaissance man.
Nice.

08:34.710 --> 08:36.330
Yeah, well, you know, uh,
knowing what you don't know

08:36.330 --> 08:37.620
is the first step
to enlightenment.

08:37.620 --> 08:40.880
You will fit right in
at Berkeley.

08:40.880 --> 08:42.330
So, did you always know
you wanted to be a doctor?

08:42.330 --> 08:44.540
I have four older siblings
who are all doctors.

08:44.540 --> 08:46.380
I'm not sure it ever occurred
to me to do anything else.

08:46.380 --> 08:47.670
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

08:47.670 --> 08:49.040
Ah, told ya!

08:49.040 --> 08:50.170
Fries.
You want one?

08:50.170 --> 08:51.960
I'm good, thanks.

08:51.960 --> 08:53.540
Uh, but Jonah's good to go.

08:53.540 --> 08:55.080
Got it, okay.

08:55.080 --> 08:56.580
Uh, hold these for me?

08:56.580 --> 08:58.540
Thanks, Doc.

08:58.540 --> 09:00.540
Till next time, brother.

09:00.540 --> 09:02.330
Mm.

09:02.330 --> 09:04.170
Until next time.

09:04.170 --> 09:06.540
Here.
And, uh, take that.

09:06.540 --> 09:07.830
You need practice, 'cause
the next time I see you,

09:07.830 --> 09:09.210
I'm-a kick your butt
for real.

09:09.210 --> 09:10.750
[ Chuckling ] Okay.

09:13.420 --> 09:14.420
All right.

09:14.420 --> 09:16.460
[ Monitor beeping ]

09:16.460 --> 09:17.670
[ Beeping ]

09:17.670 --> 09:19.290
Signal looks good.

09:19.290 --> 09:23.380
Good.
Angle looks good.

09:23.380 --> 09:26.960
So... any food allergies?

09:26.960 --> 09:28.290
Nancy will want to know.

09:28.290 --> 09:29.920
Doesn't matter
because I'm not going.

09:29.920 --> 09:31.670
[ Sighs ] Please?

09:31.670 --> 09:33.750
The begging is cute...
Don't get me wrong.

09:33.750 --> 09:35.330
And still, no.

09:35.330 --> 09:36.790
You shouldn't go, either.

09:36.790 --> 09:37.920
Life's too short.

09:37.920 --> 09:39.330
Life is too short

09:39.330 --> 09:41.580
for what it will turn into
if I don't go.

09:41.580 --> 09:43.120
One dinner with Nancy,

09:43.120 --> 09:45.540
and I avoid months
of family gossip and drama.

09:45.540 --> 09:46.710
They already think
I'm a train wreck.

09:46.710 --> 09:48.790
Well, they're wrong.

09:48.790 --> 09:50.580
Have you met me?

09:50.580 --> 09:52.290
Amelia Shepherd.

09:52.290 --> 09:55.380
Never told my family
I got divorced.

09:55.380 --> 09:57.830
Ready to attach the tether?

09:57.830 --> 09:59.460
So they don't get you.

09:59.460 --> 10:01.040
And what... they're mad
because you and Owen eloped?

10:01.040 --> 10:03.290
We didn't elope.
We had a wedding.

10:03.290 --> 10:05.920
They were invited.
They just didn't come.

10:05.920 --> 10:08.120
Wait. None of your sisters
were there?

10:08.120 --> 10:09.790
Or my mom.

10:09.790 --> 10:11.420
Or brother.

10:11.420 --> 10:13.420
He gets a pass.
Out of the country?

10:13.420 --> 10:15.670
Dead. But probably judging me
from the grave.

10:15.670 --> 10:16.750
It's complicated.

10:16.750 --> 10:19.790
That's some serious
sibling rivalry.

10:19.790 --> 10:22.710
Well, not every family
is Jonah and Brady.

10:22.710 --> 10:24.170
So why go to this dinner?

10:24.170 --> 10:26.920
[ Monitor beeping ]

10:26.920 --> 10:30.170
I was...
flown to New York

10:30.170 --> 10:32.920
to perform a rare
and complicated surgery.

10:32.920 --> 10:34.460
I'm here with my "husband,"

10:34.460 --> 10:39.330
who is shockingly handsome
and ever so kind.

10:39.330 --> 10:41.960
This dinner is a chance
for me to... I don't know.

10:41.960 --> 10:43.750
Brag?
Prove them wrong?

10:43.750 --> 10:45.040
I...

10:45.040 --> 10:46.210
I'm not sure.

10:46.210 --> 10:48.290
I'm just sure that I have to go,

10:48.290 --> 10:50.290
and that, if you go with me,

10:50.290 --> 10:52.580
I will make it worth your while

10:52.580 --> 10:56.790
in very creative ways
that you will enjoy.

10:56.790 --> 11:00.210
[ Beeping continues ]

11:00.210 --> 11:01.540
Where did we meet?

11:01.540 --> 11:03.000
At the hospital.

11:03.000 --> 11:04.790
And how long
have we been together?

11:04.790 --> 11:08.120
Years, but it feels like minutes
because love is so...

11:08.120 --> 11:09.210
Okay, we don't need poetry.

11:09.210 --> 11:10.460
We just need to keep
our story straight.

11:10.460 --> 11:12.000
What color are my eyes?

11:12.000 --> 11:14.120
You think they're gonna quiz me
on the color of your eyes?

11:14.120 --> 11:15.750
Anything is possible.

11:15.750 --> 11:17.420
♪ Naa naa naa naa ♪

11:17.420 --> 11:19.250
Sometimes they look green.

11:19.250 --> 11:20.880
Sometimes they look blue,
depending on the...

11:20.880 --> 11:22.000
Good.

11:22.000 --> 11:24.580
♪ Sunshine, blue sky ♪

11:24.580 --> 11:26.330
What is Owen's favorite pastime?

11:26.330 --> 11:27.580
Blues guitar.

11:27.580 --> 11:29.040
No.

11:29.040 --> 11:31.500
No, watching World War II
movies on PBS.

11:31.500 --> 11:33.500
But blues guitar is mine,
and Nancy's never met Owen,

11:33.500 --> 11:35.170
so can't I just answer
as myself?

11:35.170 --> 11:36.830
Well, I don't know your life.
I know Owen's.

11:36.830 --> 11:37.790
You could learn it.

11:37.790 --> 11:39.460
♪ Flying free ♪

11:39.460 --> 11:41.460
Crap.
We don't have rings!

11:41.460 --> 11:44.000
Half the surgeons I know
don't wear rings.

11:44.000 --> 11:45.380
Right. Right.
Yeah.

11:45.380 --> 11:46.420
We're surgeons.

11:46.420 --> 11:48.290
We're smart. No rings.

11:48.290 --> 11:49.670
All of that is actually true.

11:49.670 --> 11:51.670
[ Sighs deeply ]
At least it's just Nancy.

11:51.670 --> 11:54.000
Better her than Liz or...
God forbid... Kathleen.

11:54.000 --> 11:55.830
Kathleen is the worst.
Kathleen's like Martha Stewart

11:55.830 --> 11:57.670
if Martha Stewart also had
a license to diagnose you

11:57.670 --> 11:59.290
with a personality disorder.

11:59.290 --> 12:02.330
Nancy's bossy, but she's
also the most forgiving.

12:02.330 --> 12:03.460
And she does make
a really nice pie.

12:03.460 --> 12:05.750
Plus, she is gonna love you.

12:05.750 --> 12:11.790
And by you, I mean Owen,
who really likes to...

12:12.080 --> 12:13.290
Watch World War II movies.

12:13.290 --> 12:14.620
Thank you.

12:14.620 --> 12:16.000
You're gonna be great!

12:16.000 --> 12:17.250
Also, you can't drink.

12:17.250 --> 12:18.710
Owen doesn't drink.
He does.

12:18.710 --> 12:20.080
I just don't want you
to screw anything up.

12:20.080 --> 12:22.790
♪ S'My kinda happiness ♪

12:22.790 --> 12:25.710
♪ No, I won't stop ♪

12:25.710 --> 12:27.080
Link:
This is quite a place.

12:27.080 --> 12:29.750
Ah, her husband's
an investment banker.

12:29.750 --> 12:32.420
They moved here from a different
giant house in Connecticut

12:32.420 --> 12:34.080
after he got some big promotion.

12:34.080 --> 12:35.420
Wait.

12:35.420 --> 12:36.960
We never had a honeymoon...
Owen and I.

12:36.960 --> 12:38.000
He wanted Mexico,
I wanted Paris,

12:38.000 --> 12:39.540
so we did neither.

12:39.540 --> 12:41.460
Instead of doing both?

12:41.460 --> 12:42.750
Got it. Got it.

12:42.750 --> 12:44.420
No compromises, even
on the honeymoon. Mm.

12:44.420 --> 12:45.880
♪ No, I won't stop ♪

12:45.880 --> 12:47.040
♪ I got my groove, oh, yeah ♪

12:47.040 --> 12:48.670
[ Sighs ]
[ Doorbell rings ]

12:48.670 --> 12:50.920
[ Whispering ]
This is a terrible idea.

12:50.920 --> 12:52.330
[ Whispering ]
Now you figure that out?

12:52.330 --> 12:53.880
♪ With every move I make ♪

12:53.880 --> 12:55.250
You made it.

12:55.250 --> 12:57.670
- We did.
- Come on in.

12:57.670 --> 12:58.960
The house is a mess.

12:58.960 --> 13:00.120
Don't look too close.

13:00.120 --> 13:01.920
♪ S'My kinda happiness ♪

13:01.920 --> 13:03.580
You're right on time.

13:03.580 --> 13:06.250
We were just about to start
on the appetizers.

13:06.250 --> 13:08.790
We? Kathleen: Where do
you keep your corkscrew?

13:08.790 --> 13:10.420
We got to get it in
before she gets here.

13:10.420 --> 13:11.880
Is that...
That sounds like...

13:11.880 --> 13:14.540
Kathleen!
You're here!

13:14.540 --> 13:16.080
Kathleen is my...

13:16.080 --> 13:17.460
Other sister.

13:17.460 --> 13:18.880
Yep.

13:18.880 --> 13:21.960
Well, I guess
I'll put the wine away.

13:21.960 --> 13:25.080
♪♪

13:31.170 --> 13:33.040
You wouldn't have
come if you knew. No!

13:33.040 --> 13:34.540
Fun!
Family reunion!

13:34.540 --> 13:37.420
Is, uh, Liz gonna pop out
of the closet next? Or Mom?

13:37.420 --> 13:38.880
Please give me
more credit than that.

13:38.880 --> 13:40.790
I wouldn't just
spring Mom on you.

13:40.790 --> 13:42.540
I did call Liz,
but she was out of town.

13:42.540 --> 13:44.040
Ah, too bad.

13:44.040 --> 13:45.380
We could've all compared lives

13:45.380 --> 13:46.540
to make sure yours
are still better.

13:46.540 --> 13:48.460
It's not like that at all.

13:48.460 --> 13:50.750
No. This is about
Nancy's compulsive need

13:50.750 --> 13:52.250
to fix all of us.

13:52.250 --> 13:53.460
We are a family.

13:53.460 --> 13:54.830
We haven't seen each other
in years.

13:54.830 --> 13:56.500
You haven't even met Owen.

13:56.500 --> 13:58.710
I'm sure we can all be civil
for one night.

13:58.710 --> 14:00.210
[ Chuckles ]

14:00.210 --> 14:02.120
Kathleen.
Owen. [ Chuckles ]

14:02.120 --> 14:03.790
You were in the Army, right?

14:03.790 --> 14:05.420
Uh, where were you stationed?

14:05.420 --> 14:06.920
Iraq. Baghdad.

14:06.920 --> 14:08.580
[ Chuckling ]
My husband's traveling there.

14:08.580 --> 14:10.170
H-He's a diplomat.

14:10.170 --> 14:12.250
Any recommendations?

14:12.250 --> 14:15.460
Let's move inside before
we start the interrogation.

14:15.460 --> 14:18.330
The Abbasid Palace
is quite beautiful.

14:18.330 --> 14:19.920
It was, uh, built
in the 12th century

14:19.920 --> 14:21.000
overlooking the Tigris River.

14:21.000 --> 14:22.920
I'll mention it.
Mm.

14:22.920 --> 14:26.250
H-How high does the temperature
get there in July?

14:27.790 --> 14:30.880
It gets, uh, pretty hot.

14:30.880 --> 14:34.040
Um, I'm sorry.
Could I use your restroom?

14:34.040 --> 14:36.330
Of course.
Yeah, I'll show you where.

14:36.330 --> 14:37.170
[ Clears throat ]

14:39.290 --> 14:41.040
It's gonna take them
about five minutes

14:41.040 --> 14:42.670
to figure out I'm not Owen.

14:42.670 --> 14:44.210
You knew about
that palace in Iraq.

14:44.210 --> 14:46.080
Ninth grade World Civ
presentation!

14:46.080 --> 14:47.920
That's about all I remember.

14:47.920 --> 14:49.790
I-I might've been able
to handle Nancy,

14:49.790 --> 14:52.290
but that Martha Stewart one,
she's got teeth.

14:52.290 --> 14:53.620
Okay. You're right.
We got to get out of here.

14:53.620 --> 14:55.210
I mean, best case scenario,
the whole night's

14:55.210 --> 14:57.210
just them reminding me that I'm
the Shepherd's black sheep.

14:57.210 --> 14:59.460
I see what you did there.
That was the nickname

14:59.460 --> 15:00.790
that they gave me
in high school.

15:00.790 --> 15:01.920
Black Sheep.

15:01.920 --> 15:03.880
We are not subtle people.

15:03.880 --> 15:06.170
What are we gonna do?

15:06.170 --> 15:07.750
We're gonna go back out there
for a few minutes.

15:07.750 --> 15:09.290
We're gonna say
we got paged to the hospital.

15:09.290 --> 15:11.380
Because we are not
in high school.

15:11.380 --> 15:14.460
We are grown-ass surgeons
with medical emergencies.

15:14.460 --> 15:16.830
Not in high school.
Thank you for the reminder.

15:16.830 --> 15:21.880
♪♪

15:21.880 --> 15:24.380
Nancy: I'm putting the avocados
on the side for you.

15:24.380 --> 15:26.830
Oh, that's okay.
Uh, Owen loves them,

15:26.830 --> 15:28.250
so I sorta got used to them.

15:28.250 --> 15:29.460
He's great, right?

15:29.460 --> 15:32.290
Oh, I'm sure Kathleen's
got him cornered.

15:32.290 --> 15:34.380
Uh, maybe I should
just go check.

15:34.380 --> 15:36.420
[ Timer dings ]
Oh, can you grab that?

15:39.330 --> 15:40.670
[ Sighs ]

15:42.380 --> 15:45.790
You are not at all
what I pictured.

15:45.790 --> 15:47.250
Trauma surgeon.

15:47.250 --> 15:48.830
Army.

15:48.830 --> 15:51.080
I thought you'd be a lot more...

15:52.670 --> 15:54.250
Rugged?

15:54.250 --> 15:56.250
Armed?
[ Laughs ]

15:56.250 --> 15:58.210
Uptight.

15:58.210 --> 16:01.830
But Amelia loves to be
unpredictable,

16:01.830 --> 16:04.670
so... maybe it makes sense.

16:04.670 --> 16:06.460
It keeps things interesting.

16:06.460 --> 16:08.750
She has a history
of false starts

16:08.750 --> 16:10.830
when it comes to weddings.

16:10.830 --> 16:12.830
Well, we're definitely married.
[ Laughs ]

16:12.830 --> 16:16.540
I'm saying congrats on not
being abandoned at the altar.

16:16.540 --> 16:18.000
She would never do that.

16:18.000 --> 16:20.420
Oh, yes, she would.

16:20.420 --> 16:23.120
She is a Houdini-level
escape artist.

16:23.120 --> 16:24.710
First sign
things might get hard,

16:24.710 --> 16:26.670
and she is out the door.

16:26.670 --> 16:29.170
I'm surprised she didn't bolt
when she saw me here.

16:29.170 --> 16:30.250
[ Silverware clinking lightly ]

16:30.250 --> 16:32.830
She thinks we gang up on her.

16:32.830 --> 16:34.080
She provokes it, though.

16:34.080 --> 16:36.500
Honestly, I always thought

16:36.500 --> 16:40.040
she was more addicted
to drama than the drugs.

16:40.040 --> 16:41.540
But, I mean...

16:41.540 --> 16:44.290
good thing she found someone
with Army training, right?

16:44.290 --> 16:46.170
[ Chuckles ]
What's that old slogan?

16:46.170 --> 16:48.540
"No mission too difficult"?

16:48.540 --> 16:49.960
Hey!

16:49.960 --> 16:52.380
So, Jonah's scans
came back early.

16:52.380 --> 16:54.210
- We should go.
- Ah.

16:56.580 --> 16:58.580
We could review them
in the morning.

16:58.580 --> 17:02.750
Um, I know you were anxious
to see them.

17:02.750 --> 17:04.880
I think we should spend
some time with your family.

17:04.880 --> 17:08.880
Oh, um, well, we might need to
look at his labs, though.

17:08.880 --> 17:12.170
Oh, you know,
I just looked at them.

17:12.170 --> 17:15.040
And we're good.

17:16.250 --> 17:18.170
O... kay.

17:18.170 --> 17:19.170
We'll stay.

17:21.210 --> 17:22.250
[ Insects chirping,
dog barking in distance ]

17:22.250 --> 17:23.670
Nancy: Do you ever
run into Meredith?

17:23.670 --> 17:25.250
I do.

17:25.250 --> 17:27.460
I read she won a Harper Avery.

17:27.460 --> 17:30.250
Uh, they renamed it the
Catherine Fox Award.

17:30.250 --> 17:32.620
But, yeah.
Uh, she's doing well.

17:32.620 --> 17:35.380
Amelia's doing groundbreaking
research, as well.

17:36.620 --> 17:39.210
Finding non-addictive methods
of pain management.

17:39.210 --> 17:42.080
Well, Amelia would know
how important that is.

17:46.120 --> 17:48.080
How about I get that wine now?

17:50.960 --> 17:53.380
It's fine. Really.

17:53.380 --> 17:54.250
You should be more
concerned about

17:54.250 --> 17:55.880
the pills in your bathroom.

17:55.880 --> 17:57.330
I don't want to make you
feel uncomfortable.

17:57.330 --> 17:58.500
Too late.

17:59.830 --> 18:01.080
[ Cellphone ringing ]

18:03.040 --> 18:07.620
Um... I should take this.

18:11.000 --> 18:12.250
[ Sighs ]

18:12.250 --> 18:13.540
Oh, it's okay.
I'm good.

18:13.540 --> 18:15.750
Go ahead.
Amelia said you love them.

18:16.920 --> 18:18.380
I do!

18:18.380 --> 18:20.790
[ Both chuckle ]

18:26.420 --> 18:27.750
[ Leo crying ] What's happening?
Is he okay?

18:27.750 --> 18:30.500
Hey. Did you
forget to pack Roodle?

18:30.500 --> 18:31.920
I'm pretty sure
I put it in the bag.

18:31.920 --> 18:32.920
What about the one
your mom got him?

18:32.920 --> 18:34.330
Yeah, I can't find it.

18:34.330 --> 18:36.960
That's why we have a backup.
[ Crying continues ]

18:36.960 --> 18:38.880
Oh. Try giving him one of his
other stuffed animals.

18:38.880 --> 18:40.290
I'm kind of losing it over here.

18:40.290 --> 18:42.620
Well, he probably shoved it
in the couch.

18:42.620 --> 18:43.830
Okay, it's not...
It's not here.

18:43.830 --> 18:45.460
It's not... wait, wait,
wait, wait, wait!

18:45.460 --> 18:47.460
Here. Found it.
Here's Roodle.

18:47.460 --> 18:49.460
There you go.
Thank you.

18:49.460 --> 18:50.750
Can I ask you a question?

18:50.750 --> 18:52.330
Sure.

18:52.330 --> 18:54.420
What's the temperature like
in Baghdad in July?

18:54.420 --> 18:56.080
Well, once it got
to 130 degrees,

18:56.080 --> 18:57.330
and I cooked eggplant
in the sun. Why?

18:57.330 --> 18:59.120
Uhhhh, no reason.

18:59.120 --> 19:01.290
Okay. Thank you. Sure.

19:01.290 --> 19:02.880
[ Breathes deeply ]
Roodle's back.

19:02.880 --> 19:04.210
Roodle is back!

19:04.210 --> 19:07.710
♪♪

19:07.710 --> 19:09.420
[ Breathing deeply ]

19:09.420 --> 19:12.380
♪♪

19:12.380 --> 19:22.330
♪♪

19:22.330 --> 19:32.330
♪♪

19:32.330 --> 19:35.710
♪♪

19:35.710 --> 19:37.750
Kathleen: Oh, my God!
No. [ Laughs ]

19:37.750 --> 19:38.790
Nancy: No way!

19:38.790 --> 19:40.880
I don't believe you.

19:40.880 --> 19:43.620
- Oh!
- What's, uh, going on?

19:43.620 --> 19:47.080
Owen claims he can debone
the fish in one fell swoop.

19:47.080 --> 19:49.670
Well, you know, I work a lot with
bones as a, uh... Trauma surgeon.

19:49.670 --> 19:52.040
I'm impressed he knows
it's called a paring knife.

19:52.040 --> 19:54.830
[ Laughs ] I-I'm not
convinced anyone can do it.

19:54.830 --> 19:58.380
Link: Can and...

19:58.380 --> 19:59.580
did.
Aah!

19:59.580 --> 20:01.080
Oh, my God!

20:01.080 --> 20:02.880
Can you do that on people?

20:02.880 --> 20:05.710
Uh, never tried,
so I'll just say yes.

20:05.710 --> 20:08.750
Oh! We love him.

20:08.750 --> 20:11.080
And I love her.

20:12.500 --> 20:16.380
Okay. There's just one thing
I don't understand.

20:16.380 --> 20:19.790
Out of all of us, how did you
end up with the hottest husband?

20:19.790 --> 20:21.830
Aah!

20:21.830 --> 20:24.250
- Ooh!
- [ Laughing ] What? Ah!

20:24.250 --> 20:27.710
Amelia was raving about
your pie on the way over.

20:27.710 --> 20:30.040
You just made Nancy's day.

20:30.040 --> 20:31.710
I-I'll take
half that piece.

20:31.710 --> 20:34.000
Oh, you can put the other one
right on my plate.

20:34.000 --> 20:37.710
[ Door opens ]
Carolyn: I hear my girls!

20:37.710 --> 20:39.580
I didn't call her. I swear!
[ Door closes ]

20:39.580 --> 20:41.380
I may have accidentally
mentioned it.

20:41.380 --> 20:43.210
This place
is so obnoxiously huge,

20:43.210 --> 20:45.210
I can never find my way...

20:45.210 --> 20:48.080
There's my baby girl!

20:48.080 --> 20:50.330
Oh!
Hi, Mom!

20:50.330 --> 20:52.920
Oho, oh!

20:52.920 --> 20:54.000
- Let me look at you.
- [ Sighs ]

20:54.000 --> 20:55.790
- Gorgeous!
- Mm!

20:55.790 --> 20:58.380
Oh, I've always liked you with
shorter hair. [ Chuckles ]

20:58.380 --> 20:59.710
Are you going gray under there?

20:59.710 --> 21:01.330
Because your grandmother
was completely white

21:01.330 --> 21:02.540
by the time she was 35.

21:02.540 --> 21:03.880
Mom, please.

21:03.880 --> 21:05.790
And who is this handsome fellow?

21:05.790 --> 21:07.960
This is my husband, Owen.

21:07.960 --> 21:09.250
No, it's not.

21:09.250 --> 21:11.790
Of course it is.
And he's fantastic.

21:11.790 --> 21:13.960
Kathleen: You know, we were surprised,
too, but she picked a good one.

21:13.960 --> 21:15.380
Well, I'm sure he's great.

21:15.380 --> 21:17.710
But when I visited Derek,

21:17.710 --> 21:19.580
I met Owen Hunt.

21:19.580 --> 21:21.170
And this is not him.

21:21.170 --> 21:24.210
♪♪

21:24.210 --> 21:26.420
- [ Sighs ]
- Okay.

21:26.420 --> 21:28.170
I'm getting the wine.

21:28.170 --> 21:29.580
Uh-huh.

21:29.580 --> 21:31.920
♪♪

21:37.540 --> 21:39.460
Who is he?
Who are you?

21:39.460 --> 21:43.210
He's my friend and colleague,
Atticus Lincoln.

21:43.210 --> 21:44.920
You can call me Link.

21:44.920 --> 21:46.420
What the hell were you thinking?

21:46.420 --> 21:47.580
She wasn't.

21:47.580 --> 21:48.790
That's the narcissism.
[ Liquid pouring ]

21:48.790 --> 21:50.080
Were you even married?

21:50.080 --> 21:51.880
Yes! Yes!

21:51.880 --> 21:55.250
Owen and I were married,
and now... we're not.

21:55.250 --> 21:56.750
Carolyn:
You're separated?

21:56.750 --> 21:58.250
Divorced.

21:58.250 --> 21:59.920
Nancy: You were married
less than a year.

21:59.920 --> 22:00.920
Actually, a little more.

22:00.920 --> 22:02.670
But less than two.

22:02.670 --> 22:04.380
I guess.
What... What does it matter?

22:04.380 --> 22:06.290
[ Chuckles ]
Nancy and Liz owe me 50 bucks.

22:06.290 --> 22:07.620
[ Dog barking in distance ]

22:07.620 --> 22:09.040
You bet I'd get divorced?

22:09.040 --> 22:10.580
For what it's worth,

22:10.580 --> 22:11.750
I thought it would last
longer than it did.

22:11.750 --> 22:13.120
Okay, you bet on my marriage

22:13.120 --> 22:14.540
after you didn't come
to my wedding?

22:14.540 --> 22:16.290
You didn't come to my wedding.
You were in jail.

22:16.290 --> 22:17.710
She came to mine.

22:17.710 --> 22:19.040
Uncle Ron walked in on her

22:19.040 --> 22:20.460
screwing that usher
in the coat room.

22:20.460 --> 22:22.580
Carolyn: I would've come
with proper notice,

22:22.580 --> 22:26.420
but I'd barely heard of Owen
before the invitations arrived.

22:26.420 --> 22:28.790
I didn't know if there
was going to be a wedding.

22:28.790 --> 22:31.420
Okay, do you have any idea how
hurtful and insulting that...

22:31.420 --> 22:33.880
This is why I didn't even
bother to call you

22:33.880 --> 22:35.290
when I found out
I had a brain tumor.

22:35.290 --> 22:37.170
This is why.

22:37.170 --> 22:38.880
Carolyn:
Amelia Frances Shepherd,

22:38.880 --> 22:42.580
you have a brain tumor and you
didn't tell your mother?!

22:42.580 --> 22:45.040
You have a brain tumor?

22:45.040 --> 22:47.500
Are we supposed to feel better
that your fake husband

22:47.500 --> 22:49.170
doesn't know, either?
Had.

22:49.170 --> 22:52.920
I h... I had
a benign Grade I Meningioma

22:52.920 --> 22:53.750
that they removed.

22:53.750 --> 22:55.120
Nancy: Completely?

22:55.120 --> 22:56.960
'Cause this seems pretty
brain damaged.

22:56.960 --> 22:59.170
I'd say more like delusional.

22:59.170 --> 23:01.420
But, you know,
par for the course.

23:01.420 --> 23:03.790
Remember when she
bought herself that ring

23:03.790 --> 23:05.330
and she told us all
she was engaged

23:05.330 --> 23:07.120
to that guy
she dated in high school?

23:07.120 --> 23:08.290
He couldn't afford to
buy the ring himself.

23:08.290 --> 23:09.960
She got my car stuck
in the ditch,

23:09.960 --> 23:12.330
walked home,
said somebody must've stolen it,

23:12.330 --> 23:13.460
but left the keys inside.

23:13.460 --> 23:15.750
That was years ago,
and I made amends!

23:15.750 --> 23:18.460
Or when she was so drunk
at Uncle Adam's funeral

23:18.460 --> 23:20.250
that she dropped
her end of the casket.

23:20.250 --> 23:22.420
I wasn't drunk.
I was high.

23:22.420 --> 23:25.000
And, yeah, I had some bad years.

23:25.000 --> 23:26.580
You don't have to bring up
every transgression.

23:26.580 --> 23:29.710
[ Chuckling ] Yeah,
we don't have that kind of time.

23:29.710 --> 23:32.790
The point is all that crazy
happened before the brain tumor.

23:32.790 --> 23:34.120
You've always been impulsive.

23:34.120 --> 23:35.580
You don't think things through

23:35.580 --> 23:37.380
or the impact they're gonna
have on other people.

23:37.380 --> 23:38.750
You just do whatever
the hell you want.

23:38.750 --> 23:41.420
Yeah, and then you concoct
these preposterous stories

23:41.420 --> 23:43.380
to cover the truth that
inevitably surfaces.

23:43.380 --> 23:44.880
Okay, girls, that's enough.

23:44.880 --> 23:46.670
Bringing fake Owen
to dinner tonight

23:46.670 --> 23:48.750
might just be the most demented
thing you've ever done.

23:48.750 --> 23:50.210
And if you're really clean now,

23:50.210 --> 23:53.080
then we can't blame the drugs
or the tumor,

23:53.080 --> 23:55.290
which brings us
back to personality disorder.

23:55.290 --> 23:56.960
Okay, you don't know me.

23:56.960 --> 23:59.080
You have not seen me for years.

23:59.080 --> 24:01.710
I am trapped in your minds
and on your stairs

24:01.710 --> 24:04.500
at about 14 years old, and I am
not that person anymore.

24:04.500 --> 24:06.330
I am sober.

24:06.330 --> 24:08.210
I am responsible.

24:08.210 --> 24:11.120
And I am a neurosurgeon
at the top of my field.

24:11.120 --> 24:13.420
I save lives every day.

24:13.420 --> 24:15.170
In fact, I am the chief of neuro

24:15.170 --> 24:17.580
at one of the top hospitals
in the country.

24:17.580 --> 24:20.620
Because Derek was moving
and gave you the job.

24:24.250 --> 24:29.830
Listen, um [clears throat]
I'm new to, uh, all of this.

24:29.830 --> 24:31.920
And I haven't known Amelia
that long,

24:31.920 --> 24:34.670
but I wanted us to stay
for dinner tonight

24:34.670 --> 24:36.580
so you could meet the woman that
I've been getting to know,

24:36.580 --> 24:38.620
because she is not at all
the person you are describing.

24:38.620 --> 24:39.790
Link, you don't have to...

24:39.790 --> 24:42.880
She is a brilliant surgeon,

24:42.880 --> 24:46.080
the kind you fly across the
country when you need the best.

24:46.080 --> 24:47.670
She just performed a surgery

24:47.670 --> 24:50.330
that very few human beings
on the planet can do.

24:50.330 --> 24:53.330
She is a respected
teacher and mentor.

24:53.330 --> 24:55.710
She cares about her patients
and her colleagues.

24:55.710 --> 25:00.500
And she's beautiful and funny
and kind and strong.

25:00.500 --> 25:02.040
They're sleeping together,
right?

25:02.040 --> 25:04.460
Obviously. She's overcome
a lot of adversity.

25:04.460 --> 25:07.210
And, sure, she feels
her feelings in a big way,

25:07.210 --> 25:08.750
but that makes her better
than most people I know,

25:08.750 --> 25:10.830
not worse,
because it makes her authentic.

25:10.830 --> 25:15.790
She was an amazing mom to Betty,
and still kinda is to Leo.

25:15.790 --> 25:17.670
I mean, even if she doesn't
have legal custody,

25:17.670 --> 25:19.080
that baby is so lucky
to have her in his...

25:19.080 --> 25:20.000
Wait...
Did you just say "mom"?

25:20.000 --> 25:21.880
Did you say "baby"?

25:21.880 --> 25:23.750
Well... crap.
[ Sighs ]

25:23.750 --> 25:24.880
You have a baby?

25:24.880 --> 25:26.710
Baby or tumor...
Which is crazier?

25:26.710 --> 25:29.120
Who's Betty?
I'm going with baby.

25:29.120 --> 25:31.040
You never tell me anything.

25:32.580 --> 25:34.750
[ Breathes sharply ]
Come on.

25:36.250 --> 25:37.880
[ Footsteps departing ]

25:39.880 --> 25:41.790
Houdini.

25:41.790 --> 25:46.580
♪♪

25:46.580 --> 25:48.290
You okay?

25:48.290 --> 25:53.420
♪♪

25:53.420 --> 25:54.540
I said we shouldn't go.

25:54.540 --> 25:55.960
I said we shouldn't stay!

25:55.960 --> 25:57.210
Wow, okay.

25:57.210 --> 26:00.080
So your sisters are terrorists,

26:00.080 --> 26:02.460
but now I'm your problem?

26:02.460 --> 26:06.040
♪♪

26:06.040 --> 26:07.170
[ Sighs ]

26:07.170 --> 26:08.880
Look, everything was going fine

26:08.880 --> 26:12.210
until your mom called us
on our bluff.

26:12.210 --> 26:14.080
And I know it got
a little rough...

26:14.080 --> 26:16.330
A little rough?

26:16.330 --> 26:18.000
It was a lifetime

26:18.000 --> 26:20.790
of humiliating mistakes
and dirty laundry on display.

26:20.790 --> 26:22.080
I don't care about your laundry.

26:22.080 --> 26:24.330
No, I care.
You were pain management.

26:24.330 --> 26:26.040
You were my human blue light,

26:26.040 --> 26:27.500
mood-enhancing
when placed over my body.

26:27.500 --> 26:28.790
And now you know too much.

26:28.790 --> 26:31.170
And I'm... I can't.

26:31.170 --> 26:33.000
♪♪

26:33.000 --> 26:34.670
[ Cellphone chimes ]

26:36.170 --> 26:37.880
[ Scoffs ]
Son of a...

26:37.880 --> 26:39.620
Jonah's in respiratory distress.

26:39.620 --> 26:41.250
We need to get to
Fox Medical Center in Manhattan,

26:41.250 --> 26:43.670
please, as fast as you can.

26:43.670 --> 26:44.710
[ Sighs ]

26:50.580 --> 26:52.750
He's bending by the minute.
He's exaggerating.

26:52.750 --> 26:54.540
I'm fine.
I'll... I'll be okay.

26:54.540 --> 26:56.620
Ow! [ Grunts ] Jonah, we
took a look at your scans,

26:56.620 --> 26:57.960
and the tether just doesn't
...Oh, please don't say it.

26:57.960 --> 26:59.330
Your lungs are compressed.

26:59.330 --> 27:00.830
We're gonna have to replace
the rod so you can breathe.

27:00.830 --> 27:05.000
But, uh, I-I have to...
[ Groans ] I have plans.

27:05.000 --> 27:06.420
W-W-What if we tighten
the tether?

27:06.420 --> 27:07.960
That's not how it works.
I'm sorry.

27:07.960 --> 27:09.710
The rods don't work.

27:09.710 --> 27:12.460
Okay, I-I'll need new ones again
by the end of the year.

27:12.460 --> 27:14.120
The tether didn't even
last for a day.

27:14.120 --> 27:16.750
W-What if... Jonah, they said
there's no other way, okay?

27:16.750 --> 27:17.960
T-There's always
another way.

27:17.960 --> 27:19.880
That's what you said
when Mom and Dad died.

27:19.880 --> 27:21.710
I-I was scared because

27:21.710 --> 27:24.080
of how many people want to adopt
somebody with my condition...

27:24.080 --> 27:25.960
and you said that you'd
find a way, and you did.

27:25.960 --> 27:27.790
You quit law school
so you could take care of me.

27:27.790 --> 27:29.960
You can still have
big plans. Okay?

27:29.960 --> 27:31.830
Take classes here at community
co... That's not what I want!

27:31.830 --> 27:33.380
[ Sighs ]

27:33.380 --> 27:35.710
There has to be something else.

27:35.710 --> 27:37.880
A vertebral column resection.

27:37.880 --> 27:39.750
- What's that?
- Dr. Shepherd!

27:39.750 --> 27:42.380
We would remove the vertebrae
causing the curvature

27:42.380 --> 27:44.420
and replace it
with a titanium cage

27:44.420 --> 27:45.790
that would protect
your spinal cord.

27:45.790 --> 27:48.210
It's a very risky,
very complex surgery

27:48.210 --> 27:49.790
with many potential
complications.

27:49.790 --> 27:52.120
It could result
in paralysis, even death.

27:52.120 --> 27:54.420
Mm. But if it works?

27:54.420 --> 27:56.580
It would permanently correct
the deformity.

27:56.580 --> 27:57.920
You can...
You can do it now?

27:57.920 --> 28:00.040
I don't recommend it.
Yes.

28:00.040 --> 28:01.420
It is risky.

28:03.540 --> 28:05.460
But if you decide that it's
what you want, we could do it.

28:06.750 --> 28:08.540
I want it.
No, no, no, no way.

28:08.540 --> 28:10.500
[ Breathing heavily ]

28:10.500 --> 28:13.830
Look, man.
You've... Y-You had everything.

28:13.830 --> 28:17.080
Yale Law School,
tons of friends,

28:17.080 --> 28:19.210
an awesome girlfriend.

28:19.210 --> 28:21.380
Y-Y-You were even c-captain

28:21.380 --> 28:23.420
of that weird ultimate
Frisbee team.

28:23.420 --> 28:24.880
Hey, man, we were...
We were league champions.

28:24.880 --> 28:27.380
You gave up everything.

28:27.380 --> 28:29.710
Now you have h-hospital food
and waiting rooms.

28:29.710 --> 28:32.080
I like the fries here.

28:32.080 --> 28:34.040
You're the world's best brother.

28:34.040 --> 28:37.790
Okay?
Y-You're my personal hero.

28:37.790 --> 28:38.830
[ Breathing quickly ]

28:38.830 --> 28:40.620
But I'm 18.

28:40.620 --> 28:42.420
I want this surgery, and I'm
gonna do it no matter what.

28:42.420 --> 28:44.830
But I'd rather have you on...
On my side.

28:44.830 --> 28:47.250
[ Breathes deeply ]

28:47.250 --> 28:48.330
I can't lose you, too.

28:48.330 --> 28:49.460
You're not gonna lose me.

28:49.460 --> 28:51.210
This isn't the part where I die.

28:51.210 --> 28:53.580
[ Breathes deeply ]

28:53.580 --> 28:56.500
This is the part where
I'm brave and it pays off.

28:58.040 --> 28:59.500
Look at her.

28:59.500 --> 29:00.920
Look at her eyes.

29:00.920 --> 29:03.330
[ Breathes deeply ]

29:03.330 --> 29:04.750
She says she can do it.

29:04.750 --> 29:13.960
♪♪

29:13.960 --> 29:15.790
Until next time, brother.

29:15.790 --> 29:17.830
Until next time.
[ Breathes sharply ]

29:17.830 --> 29:22.120
♪♪

29:22.120 --> 29:23.750
He asked about his options.

29:26.830 --> 29:28.290
We could paralyze him.

29:28.290 --> 29:30.960
A woman just became quadriplegic

29:30.960 --> 29:32.210
on our table.

29:32.210 --> 29:33.330
That was out of our control.

29:33.330 --> 29:34.880
Exactly.
There are no guarantees.

29:34.880 --> 29:36.170
Our patient has to come first.

29:36.170 --> 29:38.000
I am putting him first.
This is what he wants.

29:38.000 --> 29:39.380
This is what you want

29:39.380 --> 29:41.170
because you've still
got something to prove.

29:41.170 --> 29:42.710
Do I need to find someone else
to do this with me?

29:42.710 --> 29:43.880
Because I will.

29:43.880 --> 29:47.460
Amelia, I'm saying
it's been... a rough night.

29:47.460 --> 29:51.460
I'm saying y-your sisters just
treated you like a teenager.

29:51.460 --> 29:53.000
They questioned
your surgical skills.

29:53.000 --> 29:54.460
I can't care what they think.

29:54.460 --> 29:56.290
You think you don't care?!
[ Scoffs ]

29:56.290 --> 29:58.420
I just spent the night
pretending I was Owen!

29:58.420 --> 30:01.210
This is not about them!
I cannot let them define me!

30:01.210 --> 30:03.620
If I did, I would still be the
messed-up baby of the family,

30:03.620 --> 30:05.580
the person that I revert to
when I am with them.

30:05.580 --> 30:06.620
And that is not who I am!

30:06.620 --> 30:09.330
I know that!

30:09.330 --> 30:11.380
I'm asking if you know that.

30:13.750 --> 30:16.120
I'm asking if you're okay.

30:16.120 --> 30:18.380
I'm asking if you are sure

30:18.380 --> 30:20.330
you're not doing this surgery
to prove something

30:20.330 --> 30:23.330
to people who clearly have
no understanding of you at all.

30:31.920 --> 30:34.670
Jonah deserves a life

30:34.670 --> 30:37.670
that is more than a cycle
of surgery after surgery.

30:40.790 --> 30:42.790
It's what he wants.

30:42.790 --> 30:44.290
And I know I can do it.

30:47.420 --> 30:48.880
Okay.

30:50.670 --> 30:54.250
♪ I remember the minute ♪

30:54.250 --> 30:55.330
♪ It was like a switch
was flipped ♪

30:55.330 --> 30:57.790
Vertebral column's out.

30:57.790 --> 30:59.250
Get me the titanium cage.
♪ I was just a kid ♪

30:59.250 --> 31:01.080
Careful of distraction
on the cord.

31:01.080 --> 31:03.540
♪ Who grew up strong enough
to pick this armor up ♪

31:03.540 --> 31:06.120
♪ And suddenly, it fit ♪

31:06.120 --> 31:08.460
♪♪

31:08.460 --> 31:13.460
♪ God, that was so long ago,
long ago, long ago ♪

31:13.460 --> 31:14.750
[ Monitor beeping ] Neurophysiologist:
We just lost the signal.

31:14.750 --> 31:16.250
The cage spread too far.

31:16.250 --> 31:17.580
There's too much traction
on the spinal cord.

31:17.580 --> 31:19.830
♪ I was little, I was weak,
perfectly naive ♪

31:19.830 --> 31:22.000
He's paralyzed. So we
revert to where we were

31:22.000 --> 31:23.540
before we lost signal.

31:23.540 --> 31:26.040
♪ And I grew up too quick ♪

31:26.040 --> 31:31.250
♪ Now you won't see
all that I have to lose ♪

31:31.250 --> 31:33.670
Dr. Shepherd...
Shh!

31:33.670 --> 31:37.710
♪ And all I've lost in the
fight to protect it ♪ Please.

31:37.710 --> 31:41.750
♪ I won't let you in,
I swore never again ♪

31:41.750 --> 31:42.960
[ Monitor beeps ]
Signal's back.

31:42.960 --> 31:44.420
I got it.

31:44.420 --> 31:46.580
He is not paralyzed.

31:46.580 --> 31:48.670
♪ I can't afford, no,
I refuse to be rejected ♪

31:48.670 --> 31:50.960
♪♪

31:50.960 --> 31:55.880
♪ I want to break these bones
till they're better ♪

31:55.880 --> 32:00.500
♪ I want to break them right
and feel alive ♪

32:00.500 --> 32:03.460
♪ You were wrong,
you were wrong, you were wrong ♪

32:03.460 --> 32:07.420
♪ My healing needed
more than time ♪

32:09.080 --> 32:15.080
♪ When I see fragile things,
helpless things, broken things ♪

32:16.960 --> 32:19.420
♪ I see the familiar ♪

32:19.420 --> 32:22.830
♪ I was little, I was weak,
I was perfect, too ♪

32:22.830 --> 32:25.250
♪ Now I'm a broken mirror ♪

32:26.750 --> 32:32.750
♪ But I can't let you see
all that I have to lose ♪

32:33.120 --> 32:36.750
♪ All I've lost in the fight
to protect it ♪

32:42.540 --> 32:45.670
No neurological deficits.
How do you feel?

32:45.670 --> 32:47.170
Like I'm going to Cali.
[ Chuckles ]

32:47.170 --> 32:48.920
How long should he, uh,
stay off his feet?

32:48.920 --> 32:50.710
A day or two.
It's good for him to walk.

32:50.710 --> 32:52.460
Ease into it, though.

32:52.460 --> 32:54.170
Your doctors here will
oversee your follow-up,

32:54.170 --> 32:55.290
but you know how to reach us.

32:55.290 --> 32:57.000
Wait. So that's it?

32:57.000 --> 32:59.710
You guys change my whole damn
life and then you just leave?

32:59.710 --> 33:01.580
Well, come see us.

33:01.580 --> 33:03.540
Seattle is a short plane ride
away from Berkeley.

33:03.540 --> 33:05.380
True.

33:05.380 --> 33:07.040
Thank you.

33:07.040 --> 33:08.540
Thank you guys for...

33:08.540 --> 33:09.830
[breathes deeply]
giving me a future.

33:09.830 --> 33:11.920
You were brave.

33:11.920 --> 33:14.120
And it paid off.

33:14.120 --> 33:16.420
[ Telephone rings in distance ]

33:16.420 --> 33:17.580
[ Wind rushing ]

33:17.580 --> 33:18.750
[ Elevator bell chimes ]

33:18.750 --> 33:21.830
[ Indistinct conversations ]

33:21.830 --> 33:23.580
Thank you, uh, for...

33:23.580 --> 33:25.290
[ Sighs ]

33:25.290 --> 33:27.170
Thank you.

33:27.170 --> 33:29.580
You were brave, and it paid off.

33:31.290 --> 33:33.580
Do you want to go for, uh...
Get something to eat?

33:35.750 --> 33:37.210
No, um...

33:37.210 --> 33:39.710
No, I need to walk.

33:39.710 --> 33:41.290
I'll see you on the plane.

33:41.290 --> 33:44.120
[ Siren wails in distance ]

33:44.120 --> 33:45.920
[ Indistinct conversations ]

33:45.920 --> 33:47.290
[ Door closes ]

33:47.290 --> 33:48.670
Brady.

33:48.670 --> 33:49.710
You okay?

33:49.710 --> 33:50.960
[ Sighs ] Yeah.

33:52.710 --> 33:54.210
I just don't know what to do.

33:56.000 --> 33:57.330
Jonah's gonna be fine.

33:57.330 --> 34:00.120
[ Chuckles ] I know.
And I'm glad.

34:00.120 --> 34:01.670
I just...

34:01.670 --> 34:05.040
I don't know what I'm gonna
do... without him, you know?

34:05.040 --> 34:07.170
Would it be weird, you know...

34:07.170 --> 34:08.250
W-w-would it...
Would it be weird

34:08.250 --> 34:09.880
if I just followed him
to California

34:09.880 --> 34:12.290
and just... I don't know...
Was... was nearby?

34:12.290 --> 34:13.420
Was...
[ Breathes deeply ]

34:13.420 --> 34:14.830
I mean, he's...
He's your brother.

34:16.500 --> 34:18.880
I get it.

34:18.880 --> 34:20.290
I miss my brother every day.

34:23.290 --> 34:25.620
But maybe try not to
follow him to college.

34:25.620 --> 34:26.880
Yeah.

34:26.880 --> 34:30.460
Maybe try to give him
some breathing room

34:30.460 --> 34:34.540
to become whoever he is
outside your shadow.

34:34.540 --> 34:37.330
♪♪

34:37.330 --> 34:38.620
And then visit.

34:38.620 --> 34:40.960
[ Sniffles ] Yeah.

34:40.960 --> 34:42.460
Thank you.

34:42.460 --> 34:50.540
♪♪

34:50.540 --> 34:52.290
[ Cellphone keys clicking ]

34:52.290 --> 34:56.290
♪♪

34:56.290 --> 34:57.290
[ Cellphone bloops ]

34:59.290 --> 35:01.210
[ Cellphone chimes ]

35:01.210 --> 35:02.670
Carolyn: Hey, kiddo.

35:02.670 --> 35:04.580
♪♪

35:04.580 --> 35:09.330
Can we... go somewhere
and, uh, talk?

35:09.330 --> 35:13.290
♪♪

35:13.290 --> 35:15.250
[ Birds chirping ]

35:15.250 --> 35:18.580
What... What happened
with Owen?

35:18.580 --> 35:21.380
It just...
didn't work out.

35:21.380 --> 35:23.460
[ Indistinct conversations ]

35:23.460 --> 35:25.750
Do you think I sabotage
relationships?

35:27.830 --> 35:29.920
That I don't know how to love?

35:29.920 --> 35:31.830
[ Conversations continue ]

35:34.750 --> 35:37.210
Well.

35:37.210 --> 35:38.670
That answers that.

35:38.670 --> 35:40.210
[ Children
talking indistinctly ]

35:40.210 --> 35:42.460
Child: I got you!
[ Bicycle bell dings ]

35:42.460 --> 35:44.460
[ Conversations continue ]

35:44.460 --> 35:46.620
I remember when you were
learning to ride a bike.

35:46.620 --> 35:49.290
[ Chuckles ]
Derek and your sisters

35:49.290 --> 35:50.830
were zipping
all over the neighborhood,

35:50.830 --> 35:52.540
and you were desperate
to join them.

35:52.540 --> 35:53.960
And so you...
You, uh, pulled

35:53.960 --> 35:55.540
that old purple bike
out of the shed.

35:55.540 --> 35:56.670
You know, the one with the...

35:56.670 --> 35:58.290
The streamers
hanging off the handlebars.

35:58.290 --> 35:59.460
Mm. Those things
were all ripped out

35:59.460 --> 36:01.380
by the time [Chuckling]
that bike was mine.

36:01.380 --> 36:04.330
[ Chuckles ] And you refused
to use training wheels

36:04.330 --> 36:06.080
because you said that
was for babies.

36:06.080 --> 36:07.580
And you wouldn't
let me help, either.

36:07.580 --> 36:10.830
I had to... I had to spy on you
from the kitchen window.

36:10.830 --> 36:13.250
You don't know
how hard that was.

36:13.250 --> 36:15.250
Watching you fall
over and over again.

36:16.920 --> 36:19.000
My other kids didn't like
to fail, but... but you...

36:19.000 --> 36:20.750
Okay.
Yeah, Mom, I get it.

36:20.750 --> 36:23.080
One time you took this...
This big spill,

36:23.080 --> 36:25.420
and you... and you
ripped open your pants.

36:25.420 --> 36:27.120
And by the time I ran out,

36:27.120 --> 36:30.960
you had pulled that...
That old ratty bike up,

36:30.960 --> 36:32.420
and... and you were
halfway down the block.

36:32.420 --> 36:34.620
Every time you fell down,

36:34.620 --> 36:36.540
you got up
and came back stronger.

36:36.540 --> 36:39.830
But not that you... that you
didn't care about falling,

36:39.830 --> 36:43.040
but... just
you weren't afraid of it.

36:45.670 --> 36:47.420
And that's what made you...

36:47.420 --> 36:48.790
What makes you...

36:48.790 --> 36:52.000
Out of all the kids...

36:52.000 --> 36:53.670
the most like your father.

36:53.670 --> 36:57.790
♪♪

36:57.790 --> 36:59.920
[ Inhales deeply ]

36:59.920 --> 37:01.500
After he died, it was hard

37:01.500 --> 37:06.170
to... be around any...

37:06.170 --> 37:09.330
Anything... that reminded me of him.
♪ All of your days ♪

37:09.330 --> 37:12.380
And... [ Sighs ] ♪
All your days ♪

37:12.380 --> 37:14.580
♪ Stay safe inside ♪

37:14.580 --> 37:16.790
...Derek said he'd watch out for you.
♪ Stay safe inside ♪

37:16.790 --> 37:18.330
And he did his best,

37:18.330 --> 37:21.380
but... he wasn't your mother.
♪ All your time ♪

37:21.380 --> 37:24.670
♪ All of your time ♪
You deserved a mother.

37:24.670 --> 37:26.540
♪ I know you can
safely hide ♪

37:26.540 --> 37:30.500
But h-he offered,
and I let him.

37:30.500 --> 37:31.830
♪ When you're living
undercover ♪

37:31.830 --> 37:34.380
[ Voice breaking ]
And it is my biggest regret.

37:34.380 --> 37:35.580
Meredith:
It turns out that,

37:35.580 --> 37:37.000
under the right conditions,

37:37.000 --> 37:38.540
neurons can recover.

37:38.540 --> 37:40.120
♪♪

37:40.120 --> 37:41.790
I took in a drug addict.

37:41.790 --> 37:43.120
♪ Though the worst
may not be over ♪

37:43.120 --> 37:46.540
Betty, Leo's birth mom.

37:46.540 --> 37:48.460
♪ You can count on me,
you can count on me ♪

37:48.460 --> 37:51.750
15, so [sighs] of course,
she already knew everything.

37:51.750 --> 37:53.290
[ Chuckles ]

37:53.290 --> 37:56.000
♪ All it could take
is a move my way ♪

37:56.000 --> 37:59.790
Parenting her was...
♪ Darling, can't you see? ♪

37:59.790 --> 38:02.790
...the hardest thing I've ever done.
♪ I will be the last to leave ♪

38:02.790 --> 38:07.080
And I'm pretty sure she was
a tenth the trouble that I was.

38:07.080 --> 38:09.750
♪ All it could take
is a look my way ♪

38:09.750 --> 38:11.580
♪ Honey, can't you see? ♪
I put you through a lot.

38:11.580 --> 38:14.210
♪ There's no more need
for hide-and-seek ♪

38:14.210 --> 38:15.540
I know it wasn't easy.

38:15.540 --> 38:17.000
[ Sighs ]

38:17.000 --> 38:18.790
I'm sorry I missed your wedding.

38:18.790 --> 38:20.960
[ Sighs ]

38:20.960 --> 38:22.620
I'm sorry I missed
your brain tumor.

38:22.620 --> 38:25.670
[ Both laugh ]

38:25.670 --> 38:28.540
I'm sorry things don't
go better with your sisters.

38:28.540 --> 38:29.710
[ Sniffles ]

38:29.710 --> 38:31.710
It's fine.

38:31.710 --> 38:33.710
Not everyone's close
to their siblings.

38:33.710 --> 38:35.790
If they can break
from normal operations

38:35.790 --> 38:37.250
and focus on healing,

38:37.250 --> 38:39.000
they have a chance at regrowth.

38:39.000 --> 38:41.500
If you don't think
you're worthy of love...

38:41.500 --> 38:43.170
♪ All of your nights,
all of your fights ♪

38:43.170 --> 38:46.540
...if you don't think your love
is valuable, you're wrong.

38:46.540 --> 38:47.830
♪ You're safe this time ♪

38:47.830 --> 38:49.710
And that's on me.

38:49.710 --> 38:51.120
♪ Though the worst
may not be over ♪

38:51.120 --> 38:52.330
Mom, I don't blame you for...

38:52.330 --> 38:53.880
Oh, oh, I...
[ Breathes sharply ]

38:53.880 --> 38:55.580
I know, hon.

38:55.580 --> 38:57.420
♪ You can count on me, you
can count on me ♪ [ Sighs ]

38:57.420 --> 39:00.250
But when you most needed help
trying to...

39:00.250 --> 39:02.290
♪ All it could take ♪

39:02.290 --> 39:04.040
...make sense of life
or...

39:04.040 --> 39:05.710
♪ Is a move my way ♪

39:05.710 --> 39:07.080
...loss...

39:07.080 --> 39:08.250
♪ Darling, can't you see? ♪

39:08.250 --> 39:09.620
...or love...

39:09.620 --> 39:11.080
♪ I will be the last to leave ♪
[ Sniffles ]

39:11.080 --> 39:12.080
...I wasn't there.

39:12.080 --> 39:13.540
♪ Honey, can't you see? ♪

39:13.540 --> 39:15.170
So put that on me...

39:15.170 --> 39:17.880
♪ There's no more need
for hide-and-seek ♪

39:17.880 --> 39:20.000
...and move forward.

39:20.000 --> 39:21.710
What if I can't? ♪ There's no
more need for hide-and-seek ♪

39:21.710 --> 39:24.290
It's human nature to want
to fix what's broken.

39:24.290 --> 39:28.380
Well...
then that's on you.

39:28.380 --> 39:29.710
♪ There's no more need
for hide-and-seek ♪

39:29.710 --> 39:31.790
[ Humming ]

39:31.790 --> 39:33.830
[ Sniffles, sighs ]

39:33.830 --> 39:35.620
♪♪

39:35.620 --> 39:37.790
[ Humming ]

39:37.790 --> 39:39.120
♪♪

39:39.120 --> 39:40.620
Man: ...the bat.
Fires.

39:40.620 --> 39:41.750
Slaps it to right.
[ Cheers and applause ]

39:41.750 --> 39:43.380
That one's gonna split the gap

39:43.380 --> 39:44.670
and head
all the way to the wall!

39:44.670 --> 39:45.830
One run is in.

39:45.830 --> 39:47.460
Here comes Beasley around third,

39:47.460 --> 39:49.170
but cut off by Montanari,

39:49.170 --> 39:51.170
and he's, of course,
standing up...

39:51.170 --> 39:53.420
[ Speaking indistinctly ]

39:56.000 --> 39:58.880
You are kind.

39:58.880 --> 40:01.170
And you were brave
last night, too.

40:01.170 --> 40:05.170
With my family.
And... And in that surgery.

40:05.170 --> 40:07.750
You didn't have to
do that with me.

40:07.750 --> 40:09.920
Either thing.

40:09.920 --> 40:12.250
You are...
[sighs]

40:12.250 --> 40:14.380
Surprising to me.

40:14.380 --> 40:15.790
And you deserve a lot better

40:15.790 --> 40:17.670
than the things
that I said to you.

40:17.670 --> 40:19.790
You are more than
a human blue light.

40:22.540 --> 40:27.710
Though you are very,
very good at bluelighting.

40:28.710 --> 40:31.080
[ Breathes sharply ]

40:31.080 --> 40:32.460
I'm sorry.

40:34.120 --> 40:37.420
And I'd like
to make it up to you,

40:37.420 --> 40:38.420
if you'll let me.

40:41.250 --> 40:43.290
[ Sighs ]

40:45.080 --> 40:47.380
[ Lucy Spraggan's
"Stick The Kettle On" plays ]

40:47.380 --> 40:55.460
♪♪

40:55.460 --> 41:00.580
♪ I know some days are hard ♪

41:00.580 --> 41:05.120
♪ But I know
how strong you are ♪

41:05.120 --> 41:07.040
Mmm. ♪ The front door's
open if you're broken ♪

41:07.040 --> 41:08.750
[ Laughs ]
Mmm.

41:08.750 --> 41:10.670
♪ Let's talk the
night away ♪ Mmm!

41:10.670 --> 41:14.540
♪ Sometimes we get it wrong,
stick the kettle on ♪

41:14.540 --> 41:15.830
Mm-hmm.

41:15.830 --> 41:17.210
[ Both laugh ]

41:17.210 --> 41:22.460
♪ I spend my nights alone ♪

41:22.460 --> 41:25.420
♪ I keep these doors closed ♪
[ Both speak indistinctly ]

41:25.420 --> 41:28.790
Meredith: We may not be able to
replicate exactly what we lost.

41:28.790 --> 41:30.080
- [ Muffled ] Oh, yeah.
- [ Muffled ] Yeah?

41:30.080 --> 41:31.120
You got a little something,
too, right there.

41:31.120 --> 41:32.170
♪ That I should just man up ♪

41:32.170 --> 41:33.790
♪ Some days we get it wrong ♪

41:33.790 --> 41:36.330
♪ Stick the kettle on ♪

41:36.330 --> 41:38.080
But in its place will grow
something new.

41:38.080 --> 41:39.670
♪ La-la-la-la, la-la-la-la ♪

41:39.670 --> 41:42.080
♪ La-la-la-la, la-la-la-la ♪

41:42.080 --> 41:43.500
♪ La-la-la-la, la-la-la-la ♪

41:43.500 --> 41:45.250
Hey!
Welcome home!

41:45.250 --> 41:49.080
How'd it go?
Uh, it's a long story.

41:49.080 --> 41:51.080
- Mm?
- So come tell us.

41:51.080 --> 41:54.750
[ Sighs ]
Well, the case went fine,

41:54.750 --> 41:56.750
but then we ran into Nancy.
[ Keys jingling ]

41:56.750 --> 41:58.580
Your sister?
Yep.

41:58.580 --> 42:00.460
Is she the snarky one?
They're all the snarky one.

42:00.460 --> 42:01.880
She invited us to dinner.

42:01.880 --> 42:03.210
♪ Sometimes we get it wrong,
stick the kettle on ♪

42:03.210 --> 42:04.540
And you went?
To her house?

42:04.540 --> 42:06.290
And I got ambushed.

42:06.290 --> 42:10.000
It's a long process, but it
happens... She was there.

42:10.000 --> 42:13.040
Slowly, but surely...

42:13.040 --> 42:14.250
♪ Sometimes we get it wrong ♪

42:14.250 --> 42:15.580
...until we have what we need.

